#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""
Apply editorial revisions to lessons 71-120.
- Breaks template drift (varied openings, structures, paragraph counts)
- Removes AI slop ("Here's the thing", "interestingly", formulaic transitions)
- Ensures genuine brain-anchors for each word
- Full particle explanations + conjugation charts for verbs
- Conjugation charts for adjectives
- Fixes known issues from review
"""
import json
import sys

# Read existing files
with open('data/lessons-051-100.json', 'r', encoding='utf-8') as f:
    file1 = json.load(f)
with open('data/lessons-101-150.json', 'r', encoding='utf-8') as f:
    file2 = json.load(f)

# Index all entries by ID
all_entries = {}
for x in file1:
    all_entries[x['id']] = x
for x in file2:
    all_entries[x['id']] = x

# === REVISED LESSON CONTENT ===
# Each entry is id -> new lesson HTML

lessons = {}

# 71: 分かる
lessons[71] = '<p>Most Japanese verbs let you be the one doing something. <span class="jp">分かる</span> refuses. In English, "I understand the problem" puts you in the driver\'s seat. In Japanese, <span class="jp-example">問題<span class="highlight">が</span>分かる</span> — the problem is the subject. It\'s the thing that becomes clear. You\'re just standing there when clarity arrives. Understanding isn\'t an action. It\'s weather.</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">分</span> is a knife (<span class="jp">刀</span>) splitting something in two (<span class="jp">八</span>). Dividing, distinguishing, telling apart. <span class="jp">分かる</span> is the moment confusion cracks open and you can see through it.</p><p><span class="note-label">分かる vs 知る:</span> <span class="jp">知る</span> is about possessing information — do you have this fact stored? <span class="jp">分かる</span> is about comprehension — does this click? <span class="jp-example">住所を知っている</span> <span class="gloss">(I know the address)</span>. <span class="jp-example">この文法が分かる</span> <span class="gloss">(I understand this grammar)</span>. You <span class="jp">知る</span> a phone number. You <span class="jp">分かる</span> calculus.</p><p><span class="jp">分かった</span> is technically past tense, but in conversation it means "got it" — an acknowledgment, not a report about history. Someone explains, you say <span class="jp">分かった</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Particles:</span> <span class="jp">分かる</span> takes <span class="jp highlight">が</span> — the thing understood is the grammatical subject. <span class="jp-example">日本語が分かる</span> <span class="gloss">(Japanese is understandable to me)</span>. You aren\'t acting on it; it\'s revealing itself to you.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Passive:</span> Rarely used — <span class="jp">分かる</span> already works like an English passive. <span class="jp-example">に分かられる</span> exists in theory but is uncommon.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Causative</span> <span class="jp-example">を／に分からせる</span>: making someone understand. <span class="jp highlight">に</span> marks the person: <span class="jp-example">子供に分からせる</span> <span class="gloss">(make the child understand)</span>.</p><div class="verb-meta"><span class="group-badge">五段 Godan</span><span class="trans-badge">自動詞</span></div><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">わか</span><span class="ending">る</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">わか</span><span class="ending">らない</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Polite</td><td><span class="stem">わか</span><span class="ending">ります</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Polite neg</td><td><span class="stem">わか</span><span class="ending">りません</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">わか</span><span class="ending">った</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Polite past</td><td><span class="stem">わか</span><span class="ending">りました</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">わか</span><span class="ending">って</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Volitional</td><td><span class="stem">わか</span><span class="ending">ろう</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Polite vol</td><td><span class="stem">わか</span><span class="ending">りましょう</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Passive</td><td><span class="stem">わか</span><span class="ending">られる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Causative</td><td><span class="stem">わか</span><span class="ending">らせる</span></td><td class="particle">を／に</td></tr><tr><td>Caus-pass</td><td><span class="stem">わか</span><span class="ending">らせられる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Potential</td><td><span class="stem">わか</span><span class="ending">れる</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Imperative</td><td><span class="stem">わか</span><span class="ending">れ</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Imp なさい</td><td><span class="stem">わか</span><span class="ending">りなさい</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～ば</td><td><span class="stem">わか</span><span class="ending">れば</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～たら</td><td><span class="stem">わか</span><span class="ending">ったら</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr></table>'

# 72: 広い - lead with comparison instead of kanji
lessons[72] = '<p>A <span class="jp">大きい</span> room might have high ceilings — volume, overall bigness. A <span class="jp highlight">広い</span> room has floor space you can move in. That\'s the distinction. <span class="jp">大きい</span> measures in three dimensions. <span class="jp">広い</span> measures in two — spread, area, room to breathe. A warehouse is <span class="jp">大きい</span>. A plain stretching to the horizon is <span class="jp">広い</span>.</p><p><span class="jp-example">広い部屋</span>. <span class="jp-example">広い道</span>. <span class="jp-example">広い心</span> <span class="gloss">(a broad mind — generosity of spirit)</span>. The word doesn\'t care which direction the space extends. If there\'s room, it\'s <span class="jp">広い</span>.</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">広</span> has the shelter radical (<span class="jp">广</span>) — a roof with one side open, extending outward. The verbs <span class="jp">広がる</span> <span class="gloss">(ひろがる, to spread out — intransitive)</span> and <span class="jp">広げる</span> <span class="gloss">(ひろげる, to spread something — transitive)</span> grow from the same root and come up constantly: <span class="jp-example">草原が広がっている</span> <span class="gloss">(the grassland stretches out)</span>. <span class="jp-example">地図を広げる</span> <span class="gloss">(unfold a map)</span>.</p><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">ひろ</span><span class="ending">い</span></td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">ひろ</span><span class="ending">くない</span></td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">ひろ</span><span class="ending">かった</span></td></tr><tr><td>Past neg</td><td><span class="stem">ひろ</span><span class="ending">くなかった</span></td></tr><tr><td>Adverb</td><td><span class="stem">ひろ</span><span class="ending">く</span></td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">ひろ</span><span class="ending">くて</span></td></tr></table>'

# 73: 数 - lead with the fun double-reading sentence
lessons[73] = '<p><span class="jp-example">数を数える</span> — <span class="reading">かずをかぞえる</span> — "count the count." Same kanji twice, different readings each time. Welcome to <span class="jp">数</span>, a word with multiple lives.</p><p>As <span class="jp">かず</span> (native reading, standalone word): quantity. How many. <span class="jp-example">数が多い</span> <span class="gloss">(there are many)</span>. <span class="jp-example">数が足りない</span> <span class="gloss">(there aren\'t enough)</span>. As <span class="jp">すう</span> (Chinese-derived, in compounds): <span class="jp-example">数学</span> <span class="gloss">(すうがく, mathematics)</span>, <span class="jp-example">数字</span> <span class="gloss">(すうじ, numeral)</span>. And as a prefix, <span class="jp">数〜</span> read <span class="jp">すう</span> means "several" — <span class="jp-example">数日</span> <span class="gloss">(すうじつ, several days)</span>, <span class="jp-example">数回</span> <span class="gloss">(すうかい, several times)</span>. Vague, small, somewhere between a few and a handful.</p><p>The kanji packs in <span class="jp">米</span> (rice), <span class="jp">女</span> (woman), and <span class="jp">攵</span> (a hand with a stick). Someone tallying grains of rice. Counting as a physical, agricultural act — not abstract arithmetic.</p>'

# 74: 近い - lead with the practical survival sentence
lessons[74] = '<p><span class="jp-example">この近くにコンビニある？</span> — probably the first sentence you\'ll actually need in Japan. It uses <span class="jp">近く</span>, the adverb form of <span class="jp">近い</span>, which pulls double duty as a noun meaning "the vicinity." <span class="jp-example">駅の近く</span> <span class="gloss">(near the station, the area around it)</span>. Learn <span class="jp">近く</span> as a word in its own right, not just a conjugation.</p><p><span class="jp">近い</span> handles both physical and abstract proximity. <span class="jp-example">駅に近い</span> <span class="gloss">(close to the station)</span>. <span class="jp-example">答えに近い</span> <span class="gloss">(close to the answer)</span>. <span class="jp-example">近い将来</span> <span class="gloss">(the near future)</span>. The <span class="jp">に</span> marks what you\'re close to.</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">近</span>: road radical (<span class="jp">辶</span>) plus <span class="jp">斤</span> (an axe). Axe range — you have to be right next to something to swing one.</p><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">ちか</span><span class="ending">い</span></td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">ちか</span><span class="ending">くない</span></td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">ちか</span><span class="ending">かった</span></td></tr><tr><td>Past neg</td><td><span class="stem">ちか</span><span class="ending">くなかった</span></td></tr><tr><td>Adverb</td><td><span class="stem">ちか</span><span class="ending">く</span></td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">ちか</span><span class="ending">くて</span></td></tr></table>'

# 75: そこ - keep short, it's a simple pronoun
lessons[75] = '<p><span class="jp">そこ</span> is "there" — but specifically there near <em>you</em>, the listener. Not far away (that\'s <span class="jp">あそこ</span>). Not here by me (that\'s <span class="jp">ここ</span>). The spot in your zone. English collapses the last two into one "there." Japanese insists on knowing whose territory the place belongs to.</p><p><span class="jp-example">そこにある</span> <span class="gloss">(it\'s there, by you)</span>. <span class="jp-example">そこに座って</span> <span class="gloss">(sit there)</span>. In conversation, <span class="jp">そこ</span> also refers back to a place just mentioned: <span class="jp-example">昨日レストランに行った。そこで友達に会った。</span> <span class="gloss">(Went to a restaurant yesterday. Ran into a friend there.)</span> The restaurant enters shared conversational space, so it becomes <span class="jp">そこ</span>.</p>'

# 76: 走る - lead with sound
lessons[76] = '<p>Say <span class="reading">ha-shi-ru</span> fast a few times. Three sharp syllables that feel like feet hitting pavement. Now say <span class="reading">a-ru-ku</span> (to walk). Slower, plodding. The sounds match the speeds.</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">走</span> was, in oracle bone script, a person running — full figure, arms swinging, legs mid-stride. Three thousand years of simplification compressed it, but the energy survived.</p><p><span class="jp">走る</span> covers every kind of running. A person: <span class="jp-example">公園を走る</span>. A car: <span class="jp-example">車が走る</span>. Pain through your body: <span class="jp-example">痛みが走る</span>. If something is covering ground rapidly, it\'s <span class="jp">走る</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Particles:</span> <span class="jp">走る</span> takes <span class="jp highlight">を</span> to mark the path — <span class="jp-example">道を走る</span> <span class="gloss">(run along the road)</span>. This is route-marking を, not direct object を. <span class="jp highlight">で</span> marks the general location: <span class="jp-example">公園で走る</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Passive</span> <span class="jp-example">に走られる</span>: indirect passive — someone running affects you. <span class="jp-example">犬に走られて追いつけなかった</span> <span class="gloss">(the dog ran off and I couldn\'t catch up)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Causative</span> <span class="jp-example">を／に走らせる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">を</span> is coercive — <span class="jp-example">生徒を走らせる</span> <span class="gloss">(make the students run)</span>. <span class="jp highlight">に</span> is permissive.</p><div class="verb-meta"><span class="group-badge">五段 Godan</span><span class="trans-badge">自動詞</span></div><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">はし</span><span class="ending">る</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">はし</span><span class="ending">らない</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite</td><td><span class="stem">はし</span><span class="ending">ります</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite neg</td><td><span class="stem">はし</span><span class="ending">りません</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">はし</span><span class="ending">った</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite past</td><td><span class="stem">はし</span><span class="ending">りました</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">はし</span><span class="ending">って</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Volitional</td><td><span class="stem">はし</span><span class="ending">ろう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite vol</td><td><span class="stem">はし</span><span class="ending">りましょう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Passive</td><td><span class="stem">はし</span><span class="ending">られる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Causative</td><td><span class="stem">はし</span><span class="ending">らせる</span></td><td class="particle">を／に</td></tr><tr><td>Caus-pass</td><td><span class="stem">はし</span><span class="ending">らせられる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Potential</td><td><span class="stem">はし</span><span class="ending">れる</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Imperative</td><td><span class="stem">はし</span><span class="ending">れ</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Imp なさい</td><td><span class="stem">はし</span><span class="ending">りなさい</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～ば</td><td><span class="stem">はし</span><span class="ending">れば</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～たら</td><td><span class="stem">はし</span><span class="ending">ったら</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr></table>'

# 77: 入れる - lead with surprising usage range
lessons[77] = '<p><span class="jp-example">電気を入れる</span> — turn on the power. <span class="jp-example">お茶を入れる</span> — brew tea. <span class="jp-example">力を入れる</span> — put in effort. Three completely different English verbs, one Japanese verb. <span class="jp">入れる</span> is "put in," and that phrase covers an astonishing range. Electricity into a circuit. Tea leaves into water. Energy into a task. Each time, something is being placed inside or activated through insertion.</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">入</span>: two strokes sliding downward into an opening. One of the most visually transparent characters in the language. <span class="jp">入れる</span> is transitive — you do the putting. Its intransitive partner <span class="jp">入る</span> <span class="gloss">(はいる)</span> means something goes in by itself. Lock in the pair: <span class="jp-example">コーヒーに砂糖を入れる</span> <span class="gloss">(put sugar in coffee)</span> vs <span class="jp-example">部屋に入る</span> <span class="gloss">(enter a room)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Particles:</span> <span class="jp">入れる</span> takes <span class="jp highlight">を</span> for what you put in, <span class="jp highlight">に</span> for where. <span class="jp-example">箱にりんごを入れる</span> <span class="gloss">(put apples in the box)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Potential</span> <span class="jp-example">が入れられる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">が</span> marks what can be put in. <span class="jp-example">まだ荷物が入れられる</span> <span class="gloss">(more luggage can still fit)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Passive</span> <span class="jp-example">に入れられる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">に</span> marks who did the putting. <span class="jp-example">コーヒーに砂糖を入れられた</span> <span class="gloss">(someone put sugar in my coffee — and I didn\'t want it)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Causative</span> <span class="jp-example">に…を入れさせる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">に</span> marks who you make do the inserting. <span class="jp-example">子供にお金を貯金箱に入れさせる</span> <span class="gloss">(make the kid put money in the piggy bank)</span>.</p><div class="verb-meta"><span class="group-badge">一段 Ichidan</span><span class="trans-badge">他動詞 — pair: 入る (はいる)</span></div><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">いれ</span><span class="ending">る</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">いれ</span><span class="ending">ない</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite</td><td><span class="stem">いれ</span><span class="ending">ます</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite neg</td><td><span class="stem">いれ</span><span class="ending">ません</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">いれ</span><span class="ending">た</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite past</td><td><span class="stem">いれ</span><span class="ending">ました</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">いれ</span><span class="ending">て</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Volitional</td><td><span class="stem">いれ</span><span class="ending">よう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite vol</td><td><span class="stem">いれ</span><span class="ending">ましょう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Passive</td><td><span class="stem">いれ</span><span class="ending">られる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Causative</td><td><span class="stem">いれ</span><span class="ending">させる</span></td><td class="particle">に／を</td></tr><tr><td>Caus-pass</td><td><span class="stem">いれ</span><span class="ending">させられる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Potential</td><td><span class="stem">いれ</span><span class="ending">られる</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Imperative</td><td><span class="stem">いれ</span><span class="ending">ろ</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Imp なさい</td><td><span class="stem">いれ</span><span class="ending">なさい</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～ば</td><td><span class="stem">いれ</span><span class="ending">れば</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～たら</td><td><span class="stem">いれ</span><span class="ending">たら</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr></table>'

# 78: 教える - lead with the surprise meaning
lessons[78] = '<p><span class="jp-example">電話番号を教えて</span> doesn\'t mean "teach me your phone number." It means "tell me." That\'s the surprise: <span class="jp">教える</span> covers both teaching (sustained knowledge transfer) and simply sharing information (a quick handoff). <span class="jp-example">英語を教える</span> <span class="gloss">(teach English)</span>. <span class="jp-example">道を教える</span> <span class="gloss">(tell someone the way)</span>. Japanese sees both as the same act — you have knowledge, you pass it on.</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">教</span>: <span class="jp">孝</span> (a child learning from an elder) plus <span class="jp">攵</span> (a hand with a rod). Teaching in its oldest form — an elder with a stick, guiding a younger person. The flow is always one-directional: from someone who knows to someone who doesn\'t.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Particles:</span> <span class="jp">教える</span> takes <span class="jp highlight">を</span> for what you teach and <span class="jp highlight">に</span> for who. <span class="jp-example">生徒に数学を教える</span> <span class="gloss">(teach students math)</span>. The person receiving knowledge takes に — they\'re the destination.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Potential</span> <span class="jp-example">が教えられる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">が</span> marks the subject that can be taught. <span class="jp-example">この科目が教えられる</span> <span class="gloss">(this subject can be taught)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Passive</span> <span class="jp-example">に教えられる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">に</span> marks the teacher. <span class="jp-example">先生に大事なことを教えられた</span> <span class="gloss">(I was taught something important by the teacher)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Causative</span> <span class="jp-example">に教えさせる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">に</span> marks who you make teach. <span class="jp-example">先輩に新人を教えさせる</span> <span class="gloss">(have the senior teach the newcomer)</span>.</p><div class="verb-meta"><span class="group-badge">一段 Ichidan</span><span class="trans-badge">他動詞</span></div><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">おしえ</span><span class="ending">る</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">おしえ</span><span class="ending">ない</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite</td><td><span class="stem">おしえ</span><span class="ending">ます</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite neg</td><td><span class="stem">おしえ</span><span class="ending">ません</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">おしえ</span><span class="ending">た</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite past</td><td><span class="stem">おしえ</span><span class="ending">ました</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">おしえ</span><span class="ending">て</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Volitional</td><td><span class="stem">おしえ</span><span class="ending">よう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite vol</td><td><span class="stem">おしえ</span><span class="ending">ましょう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Passive</td><td><span class="stem">おしえ</span><span class="ending">られる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Causative</td><td><span class="stem">おしえ</span><span class="ending">させる</span></td><td class="particle">に／を</td></tr><tr><td>Caus-pass</td><td><span class="stem">おしえ</span><span class="ending">させられる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Potential</td><td><span class="stem">おしえ</span><span class="ending">られる</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Imperative</td><td><span class="stem">おしえ</span><span class="ending">ろ</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Imp なさい</td><td><span class="stem">おしえ</span><span class="ending">なさい</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～ば</td><td><span class="stem">おしえ</span><span class="ending">れば</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～たら</td><td><span class="stem">おしえ</span><span class="ending">たら</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr></table>'

# 79: 歩く - lead with sound/physicality
lessons[79] = '<p><span class="reading">A-ru-ku</span>. Three even syllables, each one a footfall. Step. Step. Step. Compare with <span class="jp">走る</span> <span class="gloss">(はしる)</span> — sharper, faster. The sounds match the paces.</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">歩</span> was originally two footprints alternating — left foot, right foot. Over centuries the bottom morphed into something resembling <span class="jp">少</span>, but the walking is still there if you look.</p><p><span class="jp">歩く</span> is walking as transportation — point A to point B on foot. <span class="jp-example">駅まで歩く</span> <span class="gloss">(walk to the station)</span>. For aimless strolling, Japanese uses <span class="jp">散歩する</span> <span class="gloss">(さんぽする)</span> instead. Going somewhere: <span class="jp">歩く</span>. Wandering: <span class="jp">散歩</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Particles:</span> <span class="jp">歩く</span> takes <span class="jp highlight">を</span> to mark the path — <span class="jp-example">道を歩く</span> <span class="gloss">(walk along the road)</span>. Route-marking を. <span class="jp highlight">で</span> for location: <span class="jp-example">公園で歩く</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Passive</span> <span class="jp-example">に歩かれる</span>: indirect passive. <span class="jp-example">隣の人に部屋の中を歩かれて眠れなかった</span> <span class="gloss">(the neighbor walked around in their room and I couldn\'t sleep)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Causative</span> <span class="jp-example">を／に歩かせる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">を</span> coercive — <span class="jp-example">兵士を歩かせる</span> <span class="gloss">(make the soldiers march)</span>. <span class="jp highlight">に</span> permissive — <span class="jp-example">赤ちゃんに歩かせる</span> <span class="gloss">(let the baby walk)</span>.</p><div class="verb-meta"><span class="group-badge">五段 Godan</span><span class="trans-badge">自動詞</span></div><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">ある</span><span class="ending">く</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">ある</span><span class="ending">かない</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite</td><td><span class="stem">ある</span><span class="ending">きます</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite neg</td><td><span class="stem">ある</span><span class="ending">きません</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">ある</span><span class="ending">いた</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite past</td><td><span class="stem">ある</span><span class="ending">きました</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">ある</span><span class="ending">いて</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Volitional</td><td><span class="stem">ある</span><span class="ending">こう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite vol</td><td><span class="stem">ある</span><span class="ending">きましょう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Passive</td><td><span class="stem">ある</span><span class="ending">かれる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Causative</td><td><span class="stem">ある</span><span class="ending">かせる</span></td><td class="particle">を／に</td></tr><tr><td>Caus-pass</td><td><span class="stem">ある</span><span class="ending">かせられる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Potential</td><td><span class="stem">ある</span><span class="ending">ける</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Imperative</td><td><span class="stem">ある</span><span class="ending">け</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Imp なさい</td><td><span class="stem">ある</span><span class="ending">きなさい</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～ば</td><td><span class="stem">ある</span><span class="ending">けば</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～たら</td><td><span class="stem">ある</span><span class="ending">いたら</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr></table>'

# 80: 会う - lead with particle insight
lessons[80] = '<p><span class="jp">会う</span> takes <span class="jp">に</span>, not <span class="jp">を</span>. You don\'t "meet" someone the way you\'d "hit" a ball. Meeting is convergence — you move toward a person and arrive at the same point. <span class="jp-example">友達に会う</span>. The <span class="jp">に</span> marks the person as a destination, the same way <span class="jp">に</span> works with <span class="jp">行く</span>. Going to a place, going to a person — same particle, same logic.</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">会</span>: a lid (<span class="jp">亼</span>) over an opening. Things converging under one roof. The same kanji powers <span class="jp-example">会議</span> <span class="gloss">(かいぎ, meeting)</span>, <span class="jp-example">社会</span> <span class="gloss">(しゃかい, society)</span>, <span class="jp-example">会社</span> <span class="gloss">(かいしゃ, company)</span>.</p><p><span class="note-label">会う vs 合う:</span> Both read <span class="jp">あう</span>. <span class="jp">会う</span> is people meeting. <span class="jp">合う</span> is things matching or fitting. <span class="jp-example">友達に会う</span> <span class="gloss">(meet a friend)</span>. <span class="jp-example">サイズが合う</span> <span class="gloss">(the size fits)</span>. Different kanji, related but distinct — two things coming together in different ways.</p><p>You can also use <span class="jp highlight">と</span> to emphasize mutuality: <span class="jp-example">友達と会う</span> <span class="gloss">(meet with a friend — both actively participating)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Particles:</span> <span class="jp">会う</span> takes <span class="jp highlight">に</span> for the person met. <span class="jp-example">先生に会う</span>. Use <span class="jp highlight">と</span> for mutual meetings: <span class="jp-example">友達と会う</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Passive</span> <span class="jp-example">に会われる</span>: rare in natural speech. The passive idea is usually expressed differently for this verb.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Causative</span> <span class="jp-example">を／に会わせる</span>: making or letting someone meet. <span class="jp-example">二人を会わせる</span> <span class="gloss">(introduce two people — make them meet)</span>.</p><div class="verb-meta"><span class="group-badge">五段 Godan</span><span class="trans-badge">自動詞</span></div><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">あ</span><span class="ending">う</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">あ</span><span class="ending">わない</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Polite</td><td><span class="stem">あ</span><span class="ending">います</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Polite neg</td><td><span class="stem">あ</span><span class="ending">いません</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">あ</span><span class="ending">った</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Polite past</td><td><span class="stem">あ</span><span class="ending">いました</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">あ</span><span class="ending">って</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Volitional</td><td><span class="stem">あ</span><span class="ending">おう</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Polite vol</td><td><span class="stem">あ</span><span class="ending">いましょう</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Passive</td><td><span class="stem">あ</span><span class="ending">われる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Causative</td><td><span class="stem">あ</span><span class="ending">わせる</span></td><td class="particle">を／に</td></tr><tr><td>Caus-pass</td><td><span class="stem">あ</span><span class="ending">わせられる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Potential</td><td><span class="stem">あ</span><span class="ending">える</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Imperative</td><td><span class="stem">あ</span><span class="ending">え</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Imp なさい</td><td><span class="stem">あ</span><span class="ending">いなさい</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～ば</td><td><span class="stem">あ</span><span class="ending">えば</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～たら</td><td><span class="stem">あ</span><span class="ending">ったら</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr></table>'

# For IDs 81-120, I need to continue building lessons. Due to the massive size,
# I'll keep entries whose existing content is already good (just removing AI slop)
# and fully rewrite ones that are templated or weak.

# 81-100: keep existing content for entries that are already good, with targeted fixes
# The remaining entries (81-120) - for many of these, the existing content is solid.
# The key changes needed:
# - Remove "Here's the thing" from #90 (好き)
# - Vary openings
# - Fix any template drift

# 81: 書く - existing is solid, minor template-breaking
lessons[81] = '<p><span class="jp-example">空気を読む</span> was lesson 91. Now meet the other half: <span class="jp">書く</span>, the verb that turns sound into marks on a surface. Reading and writing — <span class="jp">読む</span> and <span class="jp">書く</span> — are the pair that defines literacy.</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">書</span> layers a hand holding a brush (<span class="jp">聿</span>) over <span class="jp">曰</span> (to speak). A brush that speaks — writing as speech made visible. Even though you probably type now, <span class="jp">書く</span> preserves the old connection between hand and language.</p><p><span class="jp">書く</span> covers writing and drawing, though for serious art Japanese shifts to <span class="jp">描く</span> <span class="gloss">(かく or えがく)</span>. <span class="jp-example">手紙を書く</span> <span class="gloss">(write a letter)</span>. <span class="jp-example">名前を書く</span> <span class="gloss">(write your name)</span>. In casual usage, <span class="jp">書く</span> handles both.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Particles:</span> <span class="jp">書く</span> takes <span class="jp highlight">を</span> for what you write. <span class="jp-example">小説を書く</span>. Use <span class="jp highlight">に</span> for the surface and <span class="jp highlight">で</span> for the instrument: <span class="jp-example">紙に書く</span>, <span class="jp-example">ペンで書く</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Potential</span> <span class="jp-example">が書ける</span>: <span class="jp highlight">が</span> — what can be written becomes the subject. <span class="jp-example">漢字が書ける</span> <span class="gloss">(I can write kanji)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Passive</span> <span class="jp-example">に書かれる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">に</span> marks the writer. <span class="jp-example">新聞に書かれた</span> <span class="gloss">(it was written in the newspaper)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Causative</span> <span class="jp-example">に…を書かせる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">に</span> marks who you make write. <span class="jp-example">生徒に作文を書かせる</span> <span class="gloss">(make students write an essay)</span>.</p><div class="verb-meta"><span class="group-badge">五段 Godan</span><span class="trans-badge">他動詞</span></div><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">か</span><span class="ending">く</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">か</span><span class="ending">かない</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite</td><td><span class="stem">か</span><span class="ending">きます</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite neg</td><td><span class="stem">か</span><span class="ending">きません</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">か</span><span class="ending">いた</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite past</td><td><span class="stem">か</span><span class="ending">きました</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">か</span><span class="ending">いて</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Volitional</td><td><span class="stem">か</span><span class="ending">こう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite vol</td><td><span class="stem">か</span><span class="ending">きましょう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Passive</td><td><span class="stem">か</span><span class="ending">かれる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Causative</td><td><span class="stem">か</span><span class="ending">かせる</span></td><td class="particle">に／を</td></tr><tr><td>Caus-pass</td><td><span class="stem">か</span><span class="ending">かせられる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Potential</td><td><span class="stem">か</span><span class="ending">ける</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Imperative</td><td><span class="stem">か</span><span class="ending">け</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Imp なさい</td><td><span class="stem">か</span><span class="ending">きなさい</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～ば</td><td><span class="stem">か</span><span class="ending">けば</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～たら</td><td><span class="stem">か</span><span class="ending">いたら</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr></table>'

# 82: 頭 - lead with the idiom, not etymology
lessons[82] = '<p><span class="jp-example">頭がいい</span> — smart. <span class="jp-example">頭が悪い</span> — stupid. Japanese doesn\'t dress it up with "bright" or "sharp" or "clever." You just rate the head directly. Good head, bad head. The equation of head with intelligence is universal, but Japanese wears it more openly than English.</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">頭</span> has <span class="jp">頁</span> on the right — a component that originally depicted a human head. You\'ll see it in every head-and-face kanji: <span class="jp-example">顔</span> <span class="gloss">(かお, face)</span>, <span class="jp-example">額</span> <span class="gloss">(ひたい, forehead)</span>, <span class="jp-example">顎</span> <span class="gloss">(あご, chin)</span>. Spot <span class="jp">頁</span> on the right side of any kanji and it\'s probably about something on your head.</p><p>Three readings, three lives: <span class="jp">あたま</span> is the everyday word for your physical head. <span class="jp">とう</span> is a counter for large animals — <span class="jp-example">牛三頭</span> <span class="gloss">(three head of cattle)</span>. <span class="jp">ず</span> appears in compounds like <span class="jp-example">頭痛</span> <span class="gloss">(ずつう, headache)</span>. Same kanji, completely different contexts.</p>'

# 83: 売る - lead with the buy/sell idiom
lessons[83] = '<p><span class="jp-example">喧嘩を売る</span> — to pick a fight. Literally: to sell a fight. You\'re putting a fight out there for someone to buy. And the response? <span class="jp-example">喧嘩を買う</span> — buying the fight, accepting the challenge. The buy/sell metaphor maps perfectly onto provocation and response. You already know <span class="jp">買う</span> (to buy) — now learn its other half.</p><p><span class="jp">売る</span> is transitive — you sell something. <span class="jp-example">車を売る</span>. <span class="jp-example">家を売る</span>. Its intransitive partner <span class="jp">売れる</span> <span class="gloss">(うれる)</span> means something sells on its own: <span class="jp-example">この本はよく売れている</span> <span class="gloss">(this book sells well)</span>. <span class="jp">売る</span> is your decision. <span class="jp">売れる</span> is the market\'s response.</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">売</span> has a display stand on top and legs walking below — something set up for people to come take away.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Particles:</span> <span class="jp">売る</span> takes <span class="jp highlight">を</span> for what you sell. <span class="jp-example">本を売る</span>. Add <span class="jp highlight">に</span> for the buyer: <span class="jp-example">友達に車を売る</span> <span class="gloss">(sell the car to a friend)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Potential</span> <span class="jp-example">が売れる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">が</span> — what can be sold becomes the subject. Note: <span class="jp">売れる</span> also exists as the intransitive "to sell (well)," so context matters.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Passive</span> <span class="jp-example">に売られる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">に</span> marks the seller. <span class="jp-example">友達に売られた</span> can mean "was sold by a friend" — or "was betrayed."</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Causative</span> <span class="jp-example">に…を売らせる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">に</span> marks who you make sell. <span class="jp-example">店員に商品を売らせる</span> <span class="gloss">(have the clerk sell the product)</span>.</p><div class="verb-meta"><span class="group-badge">五段 Godan</span><span class="trans-badge">他動詞 — pair: 売れる (うれる)</span></div><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">う</span><span class="ending">る</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">う</span><span class="ending">らない</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite</td><td><span class="stem">う</span><span class="ending">ります</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite neg</td><td><span class="stem">う</span><span class="ending">りません</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">う</span><span class="ending">った</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite past</td><td><span class="stem">う</span><span class="ending">りました</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">う</span><span class="ending">って</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Volitional</td><td><span class="stem">う</span><span class="ending">ろう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite vol</td><td><span class="stem">う</span><span class="ending">りましょう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Passive</td><td><span class="stem">う</span><span class="ending">られる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Causative</td><td><span class="stem">う</span><span class="ending">らせる</span></td><td class="particle">に／を</td></tr><tr><td>Caus-pass</td><td><span class="stem">う</span><span class="ending">らせられる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Potential</td><td><span class="stem">う</span><span class="ending">れる</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Imperative</td><td><span class="stem">う</span><span class="ending">れ</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Imp なさい</td><td><span class="stem">う</span><span class="ending">りなさい</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～ば</td><td><span class="stem">う</span><span class="ending">れば</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～たら</td><td><span class="stem">う</span><span class="ending">ったら</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr></table>'

# 84: 大好き - lead with cultural weight
lessons[84] = '<p><span class="jp-example">大好きです</span>, said to someone\'s face, is a love confession. This is the word that appears at the climax of every shoujo manga, every drama confession scene. Not <span class="jp">愛してる</span> <span class="gloss">(あいしてる, I love you)</span> — that exists but is almost too intense for daily use, the kind of thing married couples go years without saying. <span class="jp">大好き</span> is the sweet spot: deep feeling without crushing weight.</p><p>The construction is transparent: <span class="jp">大</span> (big) + <span class="jp">好き</span> (like) = big-like. Love. Japanese intensifies feelings by putting <span class="jp">大</span> in front: <span class="jp-example">大嫌い</span> <span class="gloss">(だいきらい, hate)</span>, <span class="jp-example">大事</span> <span class="gloss">(だいじ, important)</span>.</p><p>For things, <span class="jp">大好き</span> is enthusiastic: <span class="jp-example">猫が大好き</span> <span class="gloss">(I love cats)</span>. <span class="jp-example">ラーメンが大好き</span>. Grammatically it works exactly like <span class="jp">好き</span> — the thing loved takes <span class="jp">が</span>.</p><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">だいすき</span><span class="ending">だ</span></td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">だいすき</span><span class="ending">じゃない</span></td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">だいすき</span><span class="ending">だった</span></td></tr><tr><td>Past neg</td><td><span class="stem">だいすき</span><span class="ending">じゃなかった</span></td></tr><tr><td>Adverb</td><td><span class="stem">だいすき</span><span class="ending">に</span></td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">だいすき</span><span class="ending">で</span></td></tr></table>'

# 85: 体 - lead with the cultural phrase
lessons[85] = '<p><span class="jp-example">体に気をつけて</span> — take care of yourself. Literally: "pay attention to your body." This is how Japanese says goodbye when it means something — when you genuinely want the other person to stay well. The phrase reveals how Japanese thinks about health: through the body directly, not through abstract "feeling."</p><p><span class="jp">からだ</span> is the body as a whole system. <span class="jp-example">体が強い</span> <span class="gloss">(physically strong)</span>. <span class="jp-example">体の調子が悪い</span> <span class="gloss">(feeling unwell — "the body\'s condition is bad")</span>. You don\'t "feel sick" in Japanese. Your body\'s condition is off.</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">体</span> is a simplified form of <span class="jp">體</span>, which originally had <span class="jp">骨</span> (bone) — the body understood through its skeleton. The modern form uses <span class="jp">本</span> (root) next to the person radical: a person\'s fundamental physical self. In compounds, the reading shifts to <span class="jp">たい</span>: <span class="jp-example">体力</span> <span class="gloss">(たいりょく, stamina)</span>, <span class="jp-example">体重</span> <span class="gloss">(たいじゅう, body weight)</span>, <span class="jp-example">体温</span> <span class="gloss">(たいおん, body temperature)</span>.</p>'

# 86: すぐ - lead with spatial meaning (unexpected)
lessons[86] = '<p><span class="jp-example">すぐそこ</span> — "right there." Not "soon there" — <em>right</em> there, very close, just a few steps away. Most learners meet <span class="jp">すぐ</span> as a time word (immediately, right away), but it works for space too: no gap in distance, no gap in time. A straight line from here to there, from now to then.</p><p><span class="jp-example">すぐ行く</span> <span class="gloss">(I\'ll go right away)</span>. <span class="jp-example">すぐ来る</span> <span class="gloss">(coming immediately)</span>. <span class="jp-example">駅のすぐ近く</span> <span class="gloss">(right near the station)</span>. The kanji <span class="jp">直</span> means straight, direct — a line without bends. <span class="jp">すぐ</span> applies that directness to both time and space.</p><p>You\'ll rarely see the kanji written. <span class="jp">すぐ</span> lives in hiragana. But <span class="jp">直</span> shows up in its other readings: <span class="jp-example">直す</span> <span class="gloss">(なおす, to fix — make straight)</span>, <span class="jp-example">正直</span> <span class="gloss">(しょうじき, honest — correct and straight)</span>.</p>'

# 87: 飛ぶ - lead with the visual kanji
lessons[87] = '<p>Look at <span class="jp">飛</span>. Those two wing-like strokes fanning out on the right, the compact body on the left. It\'s a bird in flight, caught in a single character. Even after three thousand years of simplification from its oracle bone form — where it was obviously a bird with outspread wings — the flight is still visible. Few kanji are this expressive.</p><p><span class="jp">飛ぶ</span> means both "to fly" and "to jump" — any movement that leaves the ground. <span class="jp-example">鳥が飛ぶ</span> <span class="gloss">(a bird flies)</span>. <span class="jp-example">ページが飛ぶ</span> <span class="gloss">(a page is skipped — it "flies" over)</span>. <span class="jp-example">噂が飛ぶ</span> <span class="gloss">(rumors spread)</span>. The common thread: something leaves its position and moves through space rapidly.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Particles:</span> <span class="jp">飛ぶ</span> takes <span class="jp highlight">を</span> for the space traveled through — <span class="jp-example">空を飛ぶ</span> <span class="gloss">(fly through the sky)</span>. Route-marking を. For destination: <span class="jp highlight">に</span> or <span class="jp highlight">へ</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Passive</span> <span class="jp-example">に飛ばれる</span>: rare. <span class="jp-example">鳥に飛ばれた</span> <span class="gloss">(the bird flew away on me)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Causative:</span> The transitive verb <span class="jp">飛ばす</span> <span class="gloss">(とばす, to make fly, to skip)</span> is used more naturally than the causative form <span class="jp">飛ばせる</span>.</p><div class="verb-meta"><span class="group-badge">五段 Godan</span><span class="trans-badge">自動詞 — pair: 飛ばす (とばす)</span></div><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">ぶ</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">ばない</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">びます</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite neg</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">びません</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">んだ</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite past</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">びました</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">んで</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Volitional</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">ぼう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite vol</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">びましょう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Passive</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">ばれる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Causative</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">ばせる</span></td><td class="particle">を／に</td></tr><tr><td>Caus-pass</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">ばせられる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Potential</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">べる</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Imperative</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">べ</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Imp なさい</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">びなさい</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～ば</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">べば</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～たら</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">んだら</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr></table>'

# 88: とても - lead with the hidden negative meaning
lessons[88] = '<p><span class="jp-example">とてもできない</span> — "I absolutely can\'t do it." Wait, doesn\'t <span class="jp">とても</span> mean "very"? It does — with positive statements. But pair it with a negative and it flips: "by no means," "not at all possible." <span class="jp-example">とても間に合わない</span> <span class="gloss">(there\'s no way we\'ll make it in time)</span>. This was actually the word\'s original meaning — "in any case, no matter what" — and the "very" sense came later.</p><p>In its everyday role, <span class="jp">とても</span> is the neutral, all-purpose intensifier. <span class="jp-example">とてもおいしい</span> <span class="gloss">(very delicious)</span>. <span class="jp-example">とても大きい</span> <span class="gloss">(very big)</span>. It sits before whatever it modifies. No complications.</p><p><span class="jp">とても</span> vs <span class="jp">すごく</span> vs <span class="jp">非常に</span>: all mean "very" at different registers. <span class="jp">とても</span> is neutral — works everywhere. <span class="jp">すごく</span> is casual, emphatic — friends gushing about food. <span class="jp">非常に</span> <span class="gloss">(ひじょうに)</span> is formal — news reports and papers. <span class="jp">とても</span> is the safe pick.</p>'

# 89: 誰 - lead with the shapeshifting pattern
lessons[89] = '<p>Japanese question words are shapeshifters. You learned this with <span class="jp">いつ</span> (when → always/someday/anytime). <span class="jp">だれ</span> does the same thing:</p><p><span class="jp-example">だれ<span class="highlight">も</span></span> <span class="gloss">→ everyone (+ positive) / nobody (+ negative)</span><br><span class="jp-example">だれ<span class="highlight">か</span></span> <span class="gloss">→ someone</span><br><span class="jp-example">だれ<span class="highlight">でも</span></span> <span class="gloss">→ anyone</span></p><p>The <span class="jp">も</span> version is the tricky one. It flips based on the verb: <span class="jp-example">だれもいる</span> <span class="gloss">(everyone is here)</span> vs <span class="jp-example">だれもいない</span> <span class="gloss">(nobody is here)</span>. Same word, opposite meanings, controlled entirely by positive or negative. It catches people off guard but follows the same logic as English "anybody."</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">誰</span> has <span class="jp">言</span> (speech) on the left — a voice calling out, asking someone to identify themselves. The polite form is <span class="jp">どなた</span>: <span class="jp-example">どなたですか</span> <span class="gloss">(who might you be?)</span> vs <span class="jp-example">だれ？</span> <span class="gloss">(who?)</span>. The register gap is significant.</p>'

# 90: 好き - REMOVE "Here's the thing" - lead with the grammar revelation
lessons[90] = '<p><span class="jp-example">猫が好き</span>. Not <span class="jp">猫を好き</span>. The cats are the subject — <em>they\'re</em> the likeable ones. You aren\'t even grammatically present. This is one of the most important structural differences between English and Japanese: liking isn\'t framed as an action you perform. It\'s a quality of the thing liked. Cats are likeable. Coffee is likeable. Music is likeable. And you\'re the person those qualities happen to.</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">好</span>: <span class="jp">女</span> (woman) and <span class="jp">子</span> (child). A woman with a child — the image of natural affection, something precious held close.</p><p><span class="jp">好き</span> covers everything from mild preference to romantic confession. <span class="jp-example">コーヒーが好き</span> <span class="gloss">(I like coffee)</span>. <span class="jp-example">あの人が好き</span> <span class="gloss">(I\'m attracted to that person)</span>. In a confession, <span class="jp">好きです</span> alone carries the full weight of "I have feelings for you." The simplicity is what makes it powerful.</p><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">すき</span><span class="ending">だ</span></td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">すき</span><span class="ending">じゃない</span></td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">すき</span><span class="ending">だった</span></td></tr><tr><td>Past neg</td><td><span class="stem">すき</span><span class="ending">じゃなかった</span></td></tr><tr><td>Adverb</td><td><span class="stem">すき</span><span class="ending">に</span></td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">すき</span><span class="ending">で</span></td></tr></table>'

# 91: 読む - lead with 空気を読む
lessons[91] = '<p><span class="jp-example">空気を読む</span> — read the room. Literally: "read the air." The ability to sense unspoken mood and adjust your behavior is considered a fundamental social skill in Japan. Someone who can\'t is called <span class="jp">KY</span> (ケーワイ, short for <span class="jp">空気読めない</span>). The verb went from reading text to reading people, and that jump tells you something about what Japanese culture values.</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">読</span> has <span class="jp">言</span> (words) on the left. Reading is receiving words. The original meaning was reading <em>aloud</em> — in ancient China, reading was vocal, not silent. That older sense survives in <span class="jp-example">句読点</span> <span class="gloss">(くとうてん, punctuation)</span>.</p><p><span class="jp-example">本を読む</span>. <span class="jp-example">新聞を読む</span>. <span class="jp-example">漢字が読める</span> <span class="gloss">(I can read kanji — one of the most satisfying sentences you\'ll eventually say)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Particles:</span> <span class="jp">読む</span> takes <span class="jp highlight">を</span> — the text is your direct object. <span class="jp-example">本を読む</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Potential</span> <span class="jp-example">が読める</span>: <span class="jp highlight">が</span> marks what can be read. <span class="jp-example">漢字が読める</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Passive</span> <span class="jp-example">に読まれる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">に</span> marks the reader. <span class="jp-example">日記を母に読まれた</span> <span class="gloss">(my diary was read by my mother)</span> — classic adversative passive.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Causative</span> <span class="jp-example">に…を読ませる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">に</span> marks who you make read. <span class="jp-example">生徒に本を読ませる</span> <span class="gloss">(have students read a book)</span>.</p><div class="verb-meta"><span class="group-badge">五段 Godan</span><span class="trans-badge">他動詞</span></div><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">よ</span><span class="ending">む</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">よ</span><span class="ending">まない</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite</td><td><span class="stem">よ</span><span class="ending">みます</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite neg</td><td><span class="stem">よ</span><span class="ending">みません</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">よ</span><span class="ending">んだ</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite past</td><td><span class="stem">よ</span><span class="ending">みました</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">よ</span><span class="ending">んで</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Volitional</td><td><span class="stem">よ</span><span class="ending">もう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite vol</td><td><span class="stem">よ</span><span class="ending">みましょう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Passive</td><td><span class="stem">よ</span><span class="ending">まれる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Causative</td><td><span class="stem">よ</span><span class="ending">ませる</span></td><td class="particle">に／を</td></tr><tr><td>Caus-pass</td><td><span class="stem">よ</span><span class="ending">ませられる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Potential</td><td><span class="stem">よ</span><span class="ending">める</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Imperative</td><td><span class="stem">よ</span><span class="ending">め</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Imp なさい</td><td><span class="stem">よ</span><span class="ending">みなさい</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～ば</td><td><span class="stem">よ</span><span class="ending">めば</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～たら</td><td><span class="stem">よ</span><span class="ending">んだら</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr></table>'

# 92: 次 - short and punchy
lessons[92] = '<p><span class="jp-example">次は何？</span> — "What\'s next?" A tiny word you\'ll use a hundred times a day. <span class="jp-example">次の電車</span> <span class="gloss">(the next train)</span>. <span class="jp-example">次の日</span> <span class="gloss">(the next day)</span>. It always needs <span class="jp">の</span> when modifying a noun — <span class="jp">次電車</span> doesn\'t work. This marks it as a true noun, not an adjective.</p><p>In compounds, the reading shifts to <span class="jp">じ</span> and the meaning broadens to "order" or "secondary": <span class="jp-example">次第</span> <span class="gloss">(しだい, depends on / gradually)</span>, <span class="jp-example">目次</span> <span class="gloss">(もくじ, table of contents — literally "eye-order")</span>. Recognize the reading switch: standalone <span class="jp">つぎ</span>, compound <span class="jp">じ</span>.</p>'

# 93: あなた - lead with the warning
lessons[93] = '<p>Learn this word. Then learn to almost never use it.</p><p><span class="jp">あなた</span> is the textbook "you," and it\'s technically correct. But saying it to someone\'s face can sound cold, confrontational, or condescending. Japanese avoids second-person pronouns the way English avoids calling your boss by the wrong name. Use their name instead: <span class="jp-example">田中さんはどう思いますか</span>. Or just drop the subject: <span class="jp-example">どう思う？</span></p><p>The exceptions are specific. A wife calling her husband <span class="jp">あなた</span> is an established term of endearment — warm, domestic, like "dear." In surveys and instructions, <span class="jp">あなた</span> works because there\'s no specific person to name. In song lyrics, it appears constantly as a poetic, longing "you."</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">貴方</span> — "precious direction" — reveals just how honorific this word once was. Centuries of wear ground it down.</p>'

# 94: 飲む - lead with the pill surprise
lessons[94] = '<p>You "drink" pills in Japanese. <span class="jp-example">薬を飲む</span> <span class="gloss">(take medicine)</span> — not "eat," not "take," but <em>drink</em>. If it goes down your throat, it\'s <span class="jp">飲む</span>. This catches every English speaker off guard the first time.</p><p>Beyond medicine, <span class="jp">飲む</span> is the standard verb for all drinking: <span class="jp-example">水を飲む</span>, <span class="jp-example">お茶を飲む</span>, <span class="jp-example">ビールを飲む</span>. The kanji <span class="jp">飲</span> has the food radical on the left and <span class="jp">欠</span> (a person with mouth open) on the right. An open mouth near the food radical — but specifically for liquids.</p><p><span class="jp-example">お酒が飲める</span> <span class="gloss">(I can drink alcohol)</span> is how you say you drink — not as a question about what you\'re doing right now, but about capability and willingness. <span class="jp-example">飲める？</span> directed at someone is a common shorthand for "do you drink?"</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Particles:</span> <span class="jp">飲む</span> takes <span class="jp highlight">を</span> — the liquid is your direct object. <span class="jp-example">ジュースを飲む</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Potential</span> <span class="jp-example">が飲める</span>: <span class="jp highlight">が</span> marks what can be drunk. <span class="jp-example">この水が飲める</span> <span class="gloss">(this water is drinkable)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Passive</span> <span class="jp-example">に飲まれる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">に</span> marks the drinker. <span class="jp-example">最後の一本を弟に飲まれた</span> <span class="gloss">(my little brother drank the last one on me)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Causative</span> <span class="jp-example">に…を飲ませる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">に</span> marks who you make drink. <span class="jp-example">子供に薬を飲ませる</span> <span class="gloss">(make the child take medicine)</span>.</p><div class="verb-meta"><span class="group-badge">五段 Godan</span><span class="trans-badge">他動詞</span></div><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">の</span><span class="ending">む</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">の</span><span class="ending">まない</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite</td><td><span class="stem">の</span><span class="ending">みます</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite neg</td><td><span class="stem">の</span><span class="ending">みません</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">の</span><span class="ending">んだ</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite past</td><td><span class="stem">の</span><span class="ending">みました</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">の</span><span class="ending">んで</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Volitional</td><td><span class="stem">の</span><span class="ending">もう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite vol</td><td><span class="stem">の</span><span class="ending">みましょう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Passive</td><td><span class="stem">の</span><span class="ending">まれる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Causative</td><td><span class="stem">の</span><span class="ending">ませる</span></td><td class="particle">に／を</td></tr><tr><td>Caus-pass</td><td><span class="stem">の</span><span class="ending">ませられる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Potential</td><td><span class="stem">の</span><span class="ending">める</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Imperative</td><td><span class="stem">の</span><span class="ending">め</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Imp なさい</td><td><span class="stem">の</span><span class="ending">みなさい</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～ば</td><td><span class="stem">の</span><span class="ending">めば</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～たら</td><td><span class="stem">の</span><span class="ending">んだら</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr></table>'

# 95: 古い - lead with the trap
lessons[95] = '<p>Never call a person <span class="jp">古い</span>. The word is for <em>things</em> only — old buildings, old books, old traditions. An old person? Completely different vocabulary. Calling someone <span class="jp">古い</span> means they\'re <em>outdated</em>, behind the times. <span class="jp-example">その考え方は古い</span> <span class="gloss">(that way of thinking is old-fashioned)</span>. It\'s a criticism, not a description of age.</p><p>With things, <span class="jp">古い</span> pairs with <span class="jp">新しい</span> <span class="gloss">(あたらしい, new)</span>. And it can carry warmth: <span class="jp-example">古い町並み</span> <span class="gloss">(old townscape)</span> evokes charm. <span class="jp-example">古い友達</span> <span class="gloss">(old friend)</span> means a friend you\'ve known long — not a friend who\'s aging.</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">古</span>: <span class="jp">十</span> (ten) over <span class="jp">口</span> (mouth). Ten generations of mouths passing down stories. That which has been spoken of for ages.</p><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">ふる</span><span class="ending">い</span></td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">ふる</span><span class="ending">くない</span></td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">ふる</span><span class="ending">かった</span></td></tr><tr><td>Past neg</td><td><span class="stem">ふる</span><span class="ending">くなかった</span></td></tr><tr><td>Adverb</td><td><span class="stem">ふる</span><span class="ending">く</span></td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">ふる</span><span class="ending">くて</span></td></tr></table>'

# 96: 質問 - lead with usage distinction
lessons[96] = '<p><span class="jp-example">質問がある</span> — "I have a question." This is how you raise your hand in class, interrupt a presentation, or formally request information. <span class="jp">質問</span> is a deliberate, structured question — not idle wondering, not a quick aside.</p><p><span class="jp">質問する</span> vs <span class="jp">聞く</span> <span class="gloss">(きく, to ask)</span>: <span class="jp">聞く</span> is casual, woven into conversation. <span class="jp">質問する</span> is raising your hand. <span class="jp-example">ちょっと聞いていい？</span> <span class="gloss">(can I ask something?)</span> — friends talking. <span class="jp-example">質問してもいいですか</span> <span class="gloss">(may I ask a question?)</span> — meeting etiquette.</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">問</span> is a mouth (<span class="jp">口</span>) inside a gate (<span class="jp">門</span>) — a voice at the gate, calling out to ask for entry. It shows up in <span class="jp-example">問題</span> <span class="gloss">(もんだい, problem)</span>, <span class="jp-example">疑問</span> <span class="gloss">(ぎもん, doubt)</span>, <span class="jp-example">訪問</span> <span class="gloss">(ほうもん, visit)</span>.</p>'

# 97: 今日 - lead with the irregular reading
lessons[97] = '<p><span class="jp">今</span> (now) + <span class="jp">日</span> (day) = today. The logic is transparent. The reading isn\'t: <span class="jp">きょう</span> has nothing to do with <span class="jp">いま</span> + <span class="jp">ひ</span>. It\'s a native Japanese word mapped onto Chinese characters. The regular compound reading <span class="jp">こんにち</span> also exists — you hear it daily in <span class="jp-example">こんにちは</span>, which literally means "as for this day."</p><p><span class="jp">きょう</span> is a time word, so it needs no particle: <span class="jp-example">今日は暑い</span> <span class="gloss">(it\'s hot today)</span>. <span class="jp-example">今日、学校に行く</span> <span class="gloss">(I\'m going to school today)</span>. No <span class="jp">に</span> required.</p><p>The time trio — <span class="jp">昨日</span> <span class="gloss">(きのう)</span>, <span class="jp">今日</span> <span class="gloss">(きょう)</span>, <span class="jp">明日</span> <span class="gloss">(あした)</span> — all have irregular readings. The kanji say one thing, the pronunciation says another. These are among the oldest, most-used words in the language, and ancient native readings stuck even after kanji arrived. Learn them as units.</p>'

# 98: 友達 - lead with the できる insight
lessons[98] = '<p>You don\'t "make" friends in Japanese. Friends <em>happen</em>. <span class="jp-example">友達ができた</span> — literally, "a friend came into existence." <span class="jp">できる</span> means something formed, emerged, materialized. Japanese frames friendship as something that develops naturally, not something you manufacture. The grammar encodes a different philosophy of human connection.</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">友</span> is two hands reaching in the same direction — people working together, aligned in purpose. In oracle bone script, it was two right hands side by side. The kanji <span class="jp">達</span> means "to reach, to arrive." Together: your fellow-reachers, the people alongside you.</p><p><span class="jp">友達</span> is the standard, default word for friend. <span class="jp-example">友達に会う</span> <span class="gloss">(meet a friend)</span>. The word neighborhood: <span class="jp">親友</span> <span class="gloss">(しんゆう, close friend)</span>, <span class="jp">知り合い</span> <span class="gloss">(しりあい, acquaintance)</span>, <span class="jp">仲間</span> <span class="gloss">(なかま, comrade)</span>. Japanese people can be particular about who qualifies as <span class="jp">友達</span> vs merely <span class="jp">知り合い</span>.</p>'

# 99: 早い - lead with the homophone trap
lessons[99] = '<p>Two different kanji, same pronunciation, overlapping meanings — the classic <span class="jp">はやい</span> trap. <span class="jp">早い</span> is about <em>timing</em>: early, soon, premature. <span class="jp">速い</span> is about <em>speed</em>: rapid, swift. <span class="jp-example">朝が早い</span> <span class="gloss">(morning is early)</span>. <span class="jp-example">車が速い</span> <span class="gloss">(the car is fast)</span>. In casual writing, the distinction blurs and <span class="jp">早い</span> covers both. But when precision matters, the split is real.</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">早</span>: a sun (<span class="jp">日</span>) rising above a horizon. First light. Early morning. The jump from "early" to "fast" is intuitive — what arrives early moved quickly.</p><p>The compound <span class="jp-example">早速</span> <span class="gloss">(さっそく, immediately)</span> combines both kanji — early + speed — and sounds decisive in conversation: <span class="jp-example">早速始めましょう</span> <span class="gloss">(let\'s get started right away)</span>.</p><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">はや</span><span class="ending">い</span></td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">はや</span><span class="ending">くない</span></td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">はや</span><span class="ending">かった</span></td></tr><tr><td>Past neg</td><td><span class="stem">はや</span><span class="ending">くなかった</span></td></tr><tr><td>Adverb</td><td><span class="stem">はや</span><span class="ending">く</span></td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">はや</span><span class="ending">くて</span></td></tr></table>'

# 100: どれ - lead with the two-vs-three distinction
lessons[100] = '<p><span class="jp">どれ</span> is "which one?" — but only when there are three or more options. For two options, use <span class="jp">どっち</span> (casual) or <span class="jp">どちら</span> (polite). This two-vs-three split doesn\'t exist in English and it trips people up early. <span class="jp-example">コーヒーとお茶、どっち？</span> <span class="gloss">(coffee or tea?)</span> — two choices. <span class="jp-example">どれがいい？</span> <span class="gloss">(which one do you want?)</span> — three or more laid out.</p><p><span class="jp">どれ</span> is the question member of the ko-so-a-do thing series: <span class="jp">これ</span> (this), <span class="jp">それ</span> (that near you), <span class="jp">あれ</span> (that over there), <span class="jp">どれ</span> (which?). Before a noun, use <span class="jp">どの</span> instead: <span class="jp-example">どの色？</span> <span class="gloss">(which color?)</span>.</p><p>Shapeshifting with particles, same as always: <span class="jp-example">どれも</span> <span class="gloss">(all of them / none + negative)</span>, <span class="jp-example">どれか</span> <span class="gloss">(one of them)</span>, <span class="jp-example">どれでも</span> <span class="gloss">(any of them)</span>.</p>'

# === WORDS 101-120 ===

# 101: 美しい - lead with register distinction
lessons[101] = '<p>You wouldn\'t call your friend\'s new haircut <span class="jp">美しい</span>. That\'s <span class="jp">きれい</span> territory. <span class="jp">美しい</span> is reserved for things that deserve to be admired with distance and reverence — landscapes, music, prose. Five syllables (<span class="reading">u-tsu-ku-shi-i</span>) that roll out with a weight and deliberateness matching the word\'s register. It\'s formal, literary beauty.</p><p><span class="jp">美しい</span> vs <span class="jp">きれい</span>: <span class="jp">きれい</span> is everyday beauty — pretty, clean, neat (yes, it also means "clean," which <span class="jp">美しい</span> never does). <span class="jp">美しい</span> is elevated — sublime, striking. <span class="jp-example">美しい景色</span> <span class="gloss">(beautiful scenery)</span>. <span class="jp-example">美しい音楽</span> <span class="gloss">(beautiful music)</span>.</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">美</span>: <span class="jp">羊</span> (sheep) over <span class="jp">大</span> (big). A big, fat sheep — the ancient Chinese ideal of beauty was abundance, vitality, something well-fed and thriving. That origin echoes in <span class="jp-example">美味しい</span> <span class="gloss">(おいしい, delicious — literally "beautiful-tasting")</span>.</p><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">うつくし</span><span class="ending">い</span></td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">うつくし</span><span class="ending">くない</span></td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">うつくし</span><span class="ending">かった</span></td></tr><tr><td>Past neg</td><td><span class="stem">うつくし</span><span class="ending">くなかった</span></td></tr><tr><td>Adverb</td><td><span class="stem">うつくし</span><span class="ending">く</span></td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">うつくし</span><span class="ending">くて</span></td></tr></table>'

# 102: いつも - lead with the frequency scale (useful reference)
lessons[102] = '<p>Japanese has a clean spectrum of frequency adverbs, and <span class="jp">いつも</span> sits at the top: <span class="jp">いつも</span> <span class="gloss">(always, 100%)</span> → <span class="jp">たいてい</span> <span class="gloss">(usually, ~80%)</span> → <span class="jp">よく</span> <span class="gloss">(often, ~60%)</span> → <span class="jp">時々</span> <span class="gloss">(ときどき, sometimes, ~40%)</span> → <span class="jp">あまり</span> <span class="gloss">(not often, ~20%, + negative)</span> → <span class="jp">全然</span> <span class="gloss">(ぜんぜん, not at all, 0%, + negative)</span>. Memorize this ladder and you can describe any frequency.</p><p><span class="jp">いつも</span> is <span class="jp">いつ</span> (when) + <span class="jp">も</span> (also/every). When-also. Every time. <span class="jp-example">いつも早く起きる</span> <span class="gloss">(I always wake up early)</span>. <span class="jp-example">いつもありがとう</span> <span class="gloss">(thanks, as always)</span>. <span class="jp-example">彼はいつも遅い</span> <span class="gloss">(he\'s always late)</span>. It needs no particle — it works as a standalone adverb.</p>'

# 103: 足 - lead with the leg/foot ambiguity
lessons[103] = '<p>Where does the leg end and the foot begin? English draws a line at the ankle. Japanese doesn\'t bother. <span class="jp">あし</span> means both — the whole lower limb, one continuous structure. <span class="jp-example">足が長い</span> can be a compliment about someone\'s long legs or a statement about their feet, depending entirely on context.</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">足</span> was originally a picture of a knee joint with a foot below it — exactly the undivided view the word takes. As <span class="jp">そく</span> in compounds, it picks up an additional meaning: "sufficient." <span class="jp-example">満足</span> <span class="gloss">(まんぞく, satisfaction — being full-footed, having enough)</span>, <span class="jp-example">不足</span> <span class="gloss">(ふそく, shortage)</span>. A foot stepping toward a goal connects to reaching sufficiency.</p><p>When you need to be specific about just the leg: <span class="jp">脚</span> <span class="gloss">(あし, same reading)</span> focuses on that portion — especially for furniture legs (<span class="jp-example">テーブルの脚</span>). But in everyday conversation, <span class="jp">足</span> handles everything.</p>'

# 104: 起こす - existing is good, minor restructure
lessons[104] = '<p><span class="jp-example">子供を起こす</span> <span class="gloss">(wake the child up)</span>. <span class="jp-example">事故を起こす</span> <span class="gloss">(cause an accident)</span>. <span class="jp-example">革命を起こす</span> <span class="gloss">(start a revolution)</span>. Three very different actions, one verb. The thread connecting them: you raise something from dormancy into existence. Waking someone up is just the most literal version.</p><p><span class="jp">起こす</span> is the transitive half of a pair. <span class="jp">起きる</span> <span class="gloss">(おきる)</span> is intransitive — you wake up, things happen on their own. <span class="jp">起こす</span> means <em>you</em> make it happen. You cause the rising. The kanji <span class="jp">起</span> — <span class="jp">走</span> (run) and <span class="jp">己</span> (self) — captures the energy of getting up and going.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Particles:</span> <span class="jp">起こす</span> takes <span class="jp highlight">を</span> — the person or thing you wake/cause is your direct object. <span class="jp-example">子供を起こす</span>. <span class="jp-example">問題を起こす</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Potential</span> <span class="jp-example">が起こせる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">が</span> marks what can be caused/woken. <span class="jp-example">この音で子供が起こせる</span> <span class="gloss">(this sound can wake the child)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Passive</span> <span class="jp-example">に起こされる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">に</span> marks who woke you. <span class="jp-example">朝6時に母に起こされた</span> <span class="gloss">(I was woken at 6 AM by my mother)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Causative</span> <span class="jp-example">に起こさせる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">に</span> marks who you make do the waking. <span class="jp-example">姉に弟を起こさせる</span> <span class="gloss">(have the older sister wake the younger brother)</span>.</p><div class="verb-meta"><span class="group-badge">五段 Godan</span><span class="trans-badge">他動詞 — pair: 起きる (おきる)</span></div><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">おこ</span><span class="ending">す</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">おこ</span><span class="ending">さない</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite</td><td><span class="stem">おこ</span><span class="ending">します</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite neg</td><td><span class="stem">おこ</span><span class="ending">しません</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">おこ</span><span class="ending">した</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite past</td><td><span class="stem">おこ</span><span class="ending">しました</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">おこ</span><span class="ending">して</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Volitional</td><td><span class="stem">おこ</span><span class="ending">そう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite vol</td><td><span class="stem">おこ</span><span class="ending">しましょう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Passive</td><td><span class="stem">おこ</span><span class="ending">される</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Causative</td><td><span class="stem">おこ</span><span class="ending">させる</span></td><td class="particle">に／を</td></tr><tr><td>Caus-pass</td><td><span class="stem">おこ</span><span class="ending">させられる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Potential</td><td><span class="stem">おこ</span><span class="ending">せる</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Imperative</td><td><span class="stem">おこ</span><span class="ending">せ</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Imp なさい</td><td><span class="stem">おこ</span><span class="ending">しなさい</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～ば</td><td><span class="stem">おこ</span><span class="ending">せば</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～たら</td><td><span class="stem">おこ</span><span class="ending">したら</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr></table>'

# 105: 見せる - lead with the てみせる pattern (more interesting than etymology)
lessons[105] = '<p><span class="jp-example">必ず合格してみせる</span> — "I\'ll pass, just you watch." The pattern <span class="jp">〜てみせる</span>, attached to another verb\'s て-form, is a declaration of intent with a hint of defiance. You\'re not just doing the thing — you\'re <em>proving</em> you can. Compare with <span class="jp">〜てみる</span> (try doing to see what happens) — very different nuance despite the similar sound.</p><p><span class="jp">見せる</span> on its own means "to show." Historically it was the causative of <span class="jp">見る</span> (to see) — literally "make someone see." But it\'s been independent so long that it functions as its own verb now. <span class="jp-example">写真を見せる</span> <span class="gloss">(show a photo)</span>. <span class="jp-example">パスポートを見せてください</span> <span class="gloss">(please show your passport)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Particles:</span> <span class="jp">見せる</span> takes <span class="jp highlight">を</span> for the thing shown and <span class="jp highlight">に</span> for the person you show it to. <span class="jp-example">友達に写真を見せる</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Potential</span> <span class="jp-example">が見せられる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">が</span> marks what can be shown. <span class="jp-example">この書類が見せられない</span> <span class="gloss">(I can\'t show this document)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Passive</span> <span class="jp-example">に見せられる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">に</span> marks who showed it. <span class="jp-example">怖い映画を見せられた</span> <span class="gloss">(I was made to watch a scary movie)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Causative</span> <span class="jp-example">に見せさせる</span>: making someone show something. Rare — <span class="jp">見せる</span> already contains causative meaning.</p><div class="verb-meta"><span class="group-badge">一段 Ichidan</span><span class="trans-badge">他動詞</span></div><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">みせ</span><span class="ending">る</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">みせ</span><span class="ending">ない</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite</td><td><span class="stem">みせ</span><span class="ending">ます</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite neg</td><td><span class="stem">みせ</span><span class="ending">ません</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">みせ</span><span class="ending">た</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite past</td><td><span class="stem">みせ</span><span class="ending">ました</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">みせ</span><span class="ending">て</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Volitional</td><td><span class="stem">みせ</span><span class="ending">よう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite vol</td><td><span class="stem">みせ</span><span class="ending">ましょう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Passive</td><td><span class="stem">みせ</span><span class="ending">られる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Causative</td><td><span class="stem">みせ</span><span class="ending">させる</span></td><td class="particle">に／を</td></tr><tr><td>Caus-pass</td><td><span class="stem">みせ</span><span class="ending">させられる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Potential</td><td><span class="stem">みせ</span><span class="ending">られる</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Imperative</td><td><span class="stem">みせ</span><span class="ending">ろ</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Imp なさい</td><td><span class="stem">みせ</span><span class="ending">なさい</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～ば</td><td><span class="stem">みせ</span><span class="ending">れば</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～たら</td><td><span class="stem">みせ</span><span class="ending">たら</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr></table>'

# 106: 娘 - lead with the humble/respectful split
lessons[106] = '<p><span class="jp-example">うちの娘</span> — "my daughter." <span class="jp-example">お嬢さん</span> — "your daughter." Two completely different words for the same family member, depending on whose daughter you\'re talking about. <span class="jp">娘</span> is humble — you use it for your own children. For someone else\'s daughter, the respectful term is <span class="jp">お嬢さん</span> <span class="gloss">(おじょうさん)</span>. This humble/respectful split runs through all Japanese family vocabulary.</p><p><span class="jp">むすめ</span> also means "young woman" in older or literary writing — <span class="jp-example">あの娘</span> <span class="gloss">(that girl)</span>. The kanji <span class="jp">娘</span> is <span class="jp">女</span> (woman) plus <span class="jp">良</span> (good). A "good woman" meant a young, unmarried one in the society that created this character.</p><p>Its pair: <span class="jp">息子</span> <span class="gloss">(むすこ, son)</span>. Together they cover your children in humble speech. But there\'s an asymmetry — <span class="jp">娘</span> can mean any young woman, while <span class="jp">息子</span> only ever means "son."</p>'

# 107: 楽しむ - lead with the kanji\'s origin (drum)
lessons[107] = '<p>The kanji <span class="jp">楽</span> started as a picture of a drum on a wooden stand — a musical instrument. From music came pleasure. From pleasure came ease. That\'s why <span class="jp">楽</span> has such range: <span class="jp">楽しい</span> (fun), <span class="jp">楽</span> (easy/comfortable), <span class="jp">音楽</span> (music). They\'re all branches growing from a drumbeat.</p><p><span class="jp">楽しむ</span> is the verb — to actively enjoy something, to choose to find joy. <span class="jp-example">旅行を楽しむ</span>. <span class="jp-example">人生を楽しむ</span>. Unlike the adjective <span class="jp">楽しい</span> (which describes a state), the verb implies deliberate engagement.</p><p><span class="jp-example">楽しみにしている</span> <span class="gloss">(I\'m looking forward to it)</span> — memorize this as a unit. It uses the noun form <span class="jp">楽しみ</span> and is one of the most useful phrases in Japanese.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Particles:</span> <span class="jp">楽しむ</span> takes <span class="jp highlight">を</span> — the experience is your direct object. <span class="jp-example">休みを楽しむ</span> <span class="gloss">(enjoy the holiday)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Potential</span> <span class="jp-example">が楽しめる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">が</span> marks what can be enjoyed. <span class="jp-example">ここで景色が楽しめる</span> <span class="gloss">(the scenery here can be enjoyed)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Passive</span> <span class="jp-example">に楽しまれる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">に</span> marks who enjoys it. <span class="jp-example">世界中の人に楽しまれている</span> <span class="gloss">(enjoyed by people worldwide)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Causative</span> <span class="jp-example">を楽しませる</span>: commonly used as "to entertain" — <span class="jp-example">お客さんを楽しませる</span> <span class="gloss">(entertain the guests)</span>. Making someone experience enjoyment.</p><div class="verb-meta"><span class="group-badge">五段 Godan</span><span class="trans-badge">他動詞</span></div><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">たのし</span><span class="ending">む</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">たのし</span><span class="ending">まない</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite</td><td><span class="stem">たのし</span><span class="ending">みます</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite neg</td><td><span class="stem">たのし</span><span class="ending">みません</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">たのし</span><span class="ending">んだ</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite past</td><td><span class="stem">たのし</span><span class="ending">みました</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">たのし</span><span class="ending">んで</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Volitional</td><td><span class="stem">たのし</span><span class="ending">もう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite vol</td><td><span class="stem">たのし</span><span class="ending">みましょう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Passive</td><td><span class="stem">たのし</span><span class="ending">まれる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Causative</td><td><span class="stem">たのし</span><span class="ending">ませる</span></td><td class="particle">に／を</td></tr><tr><td>Caus-pass</td><td><span class="stem">たのし</span><span class="ending">ませられる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Potential</td><td><span class="stem">たのし</span><span class="ending">める</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Imperative</td><td><span class="stem">たのし</span><span class="ending">め</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Imp なさい</td><td><span class="stem">たのし</span><span class="ending">みなさい</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～ば</td><td><span class="stem">たのし</span><span class="ending">めば</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～たら</td><td><span class="stem">たのし</span><span class="ending">んだら</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr></table>'

# 108: 色 - lead with the scandalous etymology
lessons[108] = '<p>The kanji <span class="jp">色</span> originally had nothing to do with color. It depicted a person kneeling over another — the posture of intimacy. Its oldest meaning was sexual desire, passion, beauty. The shift to "color" came through complexion: the flush of emotion on skin, the visual surface of feeling. That earlier meaning never fully left: <span class="jp-example">色っぽい</span> <span class="gloss">(いろっぽい, sexy)</span> and <span class="jp-example">色気</span> <span class="gloss">(いろけ, sex appeal)</span> use <span class="jp">色</span> in its original sense.</p><p>As "color," <span class="jp">いろ</span> is the basic word. <span class="jp-example">何色？</span> <span class="gloss">(なにいろ, what color?)</span>. Colors attach directly: <span class="jp-example">赤色</span>, <span class="jp-example">青色</span>, <span class="jp-example">黄色</span> <span class="gloss">(きいろ — notably the only basic color requiring <span class="jp">色</span> even in its short form)</span>.</p><p><span class="jp-example">色々</span> <span class="gloss">(いろいろ, various)</span> — literally "colors and colors," meaning many different kinds. One of the most common words in Japanese. Different colors, different types, all mixed together.</p>'

# 109: みんな - lead with the "all" vs "everyone" trap
lessons[109] = '<p><span class="jp-example">お菓子をみんな食べた</span> — "ate all the snacks." Not "everyone ate the snacks" — <em>all</em> the snacks. <span class="jp">みんな</span> can mean "all of something," not just "all people." This trips learners up. It refers to the entirety of whatever it modifies, whether that\'s a group of people or a plate of cookies.</p><p>As "everyone": <span class="jp-example">みんな来た</span> <span class="gloss">(everyone came)</span>. <span class="jp-example">みんなの意見</span> <span class="gloss">(everyone\'s opinion)</span>. The word comes from <span class="jp">皆</span> <span class="gloss">(みな)</span> with an inserted <span class="jp">ん</span> for easier pronunciation. <span class="jp">みな</span> is slightly more formal; <span class="jp">みんな</span> is casual and warm.</p><p>The polite form <span class="jp">皆さん</span> <span class="gloss">(みなさん)</span> adds respectful <span class="jp">さん</span>. Teachers to classes, speakers to audiences, announcements to the public — all <span class="jp">皆さん</span>. Friends to friends — <span class="jp">みんな</span>.</p>'

# 110: 取る - lead with the brutal etymology
lessons[110] = '<p>The kanji <span class="jp">取</span>: <span class="jp">耳</span> (ear) plus <span class="jp">又</span> (hand). A hand grabbing an ear. This isn\'t metaphor — in ancient warfare, soldiers took enemies\' ears as proof of kills. The kanji preserves that origin: to seize, to claim.</p><p>Modern <span class="jp">取る</span> shed the violence but kept the breadth. It\'s one of the most overloaded verbs in Japanese: <span class="jp-example">写真を撮る</span> <span class="gloss">(take a photo — 撮る is more specific)</span>. <span class="jp-example">休みを取る</span> <span class="gloss">(take time off)</span>. <span class="jp-example">メモを取る</span> <span class="gloss">(take notes)</span>. <span class="jp-example">年を取る</span> <span class="gloss">(age — "take years")</span>. Physical objects, abstract concepts, spans of time — it doesn\'t care.</p><p><span class="note-label">取る vs 撮る vs 採る:</span> All read <span class="jp">とる</span>. <span class="jp">取る</span> is the default. <span class="jp">撮る</span> is for photos/video. <span class="jp">採る</span> is harvesting or adopting measures. In casual writing, <span class="jp">取る</span> or hiragana <span class="jp">とる</span> covers everything.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Particles:</span> <span class="jp">取る</span> takes <span class="jp highlight">を</span> — the thing taken is your direct object. <span class="jp-example">塩を取って</span> <span class="gloss">(pass the salt)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Potential</span> <span class="jp-example">が取れる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">が</span> marks what can be taken. <span class="jp-example">休みが取れる</span> <span class="gloss">(I can take time off)</span>. Note: <span class="jp">取れる</span> also means "to come off" — <span class="jp-example">ボタンが取れた</span> <span class="gloss">(the button came off)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Passive</span> <span class="jp-example">に取られる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">に</span> marks who took it. <span class="jp-example">猫に魚を取られた</span> <span class="gloss">(the cat took my fish)</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Causative</span> <span class="jp-example">に…を取らせる</span>: <span class="jp highlight">に</span> marks who you make take. <span class="jp-example">生徒にメモを取らせる</span> <span class="gloss">(have students take notes)</span>.</p><div class="verb-meta"><span class="group-badge">五段 Godan</span><span class="trans-badge">他動詞</span></div><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">る</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">らない</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">ります</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite neg</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">りません</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">った</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite past</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">りました</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">って</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Volitional</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">ろう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Polite vol</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">りましょう</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Passive</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">られる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Causative</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">らせる</span></td><td class="particle">に／を</td></tr><tr><td>Caus-pass</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">らせられる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Potential</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">れる</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Imperative</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">れ</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Imp なさい</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">りなさい</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～ば</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">れば</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～たら</td><td><span class="stem">と</span><span class="ending">ったら</span></td><td class="particle">を</td></tr></table>'

# 111: 勉強 - lead with the Chinese meaning difference
lessons[111] = '<p>In Chinese, 勉強 (miǎnqiǎng) means "reluctant" — forcing yourself to do something you\'d rather not. Japanese took that core sense and narrowed it to the most common thing people force themselves to do: study. The honesty is baked into the kanji: <span class="jp">勉</span> (exert oneself) + <span class="jp">強</span> (strong, to force). Studying as an act of willpower. The word doesn\'t pretend it\'s fun.</p><p><span class="jp">勉強する</span> is a する-noun: <span class="jp-example">日本語を勉強する</span> <span class="gloss">(study Japanese)</span>. You\'ll also hear <span class="jp-example">勉強になる</span> <span class="gloss">("it becomes studying" → I learned something, that was informative)</span> — a polite way to acknowledge someone taught you something. Use it after receiving useful information and you\'ll sound appreciative.</p>'

# 112: できる - lead with the dual identity
lessons[112] = '<p><span class="jp">できる</span> is two verbs wearing one mask. <span class="jp-example">日本語ができる</span> <span class="gloss">(I can speak Japanese)</span> — ability. <span class="jp-example">準備ができた</span> <span class="gloss">(preparations are done)</span> — completion. <span class="jp-example">友達ができた</span> <span class="gloss">(I made a friend — a friend came into being)</span> — something materializing. The connection: if something <em>can</em> be done, it <em>gets</em> done. Ability and completion are two sides of one coin.</p><p>Technically <span class="jp">できる</span> is the potential form of <span class="jp">する</span>, but it\'s so independent that nobody thinks of it that way. It takes <span class="jp highlight">が</span>, not <span class="jp">を</span> — the thing that\'s possible is the subject: <span class="jp-example">英語<span class="highlight">が</span>できる</span>. Same pattern as <span class="jp">分かる</span> and <span class="jp">好き</span>.</p><p><span class="jp-example">できるだけ早く</span> <span class="gloss">(as fast as possible)</span> — memorize this phrase as a block. "To the extent that can be done." Extremely common.</p><div class="verb-meta"><span class="group-badge">一段 Ichidan</span><span class="trans-badge">自動詞</span></div><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">でき</span><span class="ending">る</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">でき</span><span class="ending">ない</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Polite</td><td><span class="stem">でき</span><span class="ending">ます</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Polite neg</td><td><span class="stem">でき</span><span class="ending">ません</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">でき</span><span class="ending">た</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Polite past</td><td><span class="stem">でき</span><span class="ending">ました</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">でき</span><span class="ending">て</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Volitional</td><td><span class="stem">でき</span><span class="ending">よう</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Polite vol</td><td><span class="stem">でき</span><span class="ending">ましょう</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Passive</td><td><span class="stem">でき</span><span class="ending">られる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Causative</td><td><span class="stem">でき</span><span class="ending">させる</span></td><td class="particle">を／に</td></tr><tr><td>Caus-pass</td><td><span class="stem">でき</span><span class="ending">させられる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Potential</td><td><span class="stem">でき</span><span class="ending">る</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Imperative</td><td><span class="stem">でき</span><span class="ending">ろ</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Imp なさい</td><td><span class="stem">でき</span><span class="ending">なさい</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～ば</td><td><span class="stem">でき</span><span class="ending">れば</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～たら</td><td><span class="stem">でき</span><span class="ending">たら</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr></table>'

# 113: 短い - lead with the irony
lessons[113] = '<p><span class="reading">Mi-ji-ka-i</span> — four syllables for a word meaning "short." Its opposite, <span class="jp">長い</span> <span class="gloss">(ながい, long)</span>, has fewer syllables. Don\'t look for logic there, but it makes a decent mnemonic: <span class="jp">みじかい</span> is so long it overflows its own meaning.</p><p><span class="jp">短い</span> covers length, duration, and distance. <span class="jp-example">短いスカート</span>. <span class="jp-example">短い時間</span>. <span class="jp-example">短い距離</span>. But not height — a short person isn\'t <span class="jp">短い</span>, they\'re <span class="jp">背が低い</span> <span class="gloss">(せがひくい, low in stature)</span>. English speakers mix this up constantly.</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">短</span>: <span class="jp">矢</span> (arrow) plus <span class="jp">豆</span> (bean). An arrow as small as a bean — short.</p><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">みじか</span><span class="ending">い</span></td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">みじか</span><span class="ending">くない</span></td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">みじか</span><span class="ending">かった</span></td></tr><tr><td>Past neg</td><td><span class="stem">みじか</span><span class="ending">くなかった</span></td></tr><tr><td>Adverb</td><td><span class="stem">みじか</span><span class="ending">く</span></td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">みじか</span><span class="ending">くて</span></td></tr></table>'

# 114: 落ちる - lead with exam failure meaning
lessons[114] = '<p><span class="jp-example">試験に落ちた</span> — "I failed the exam." Not <span class="jp">失敗した</span> (general failure). Exam failure is <em>falling</em>. And the opposite? <span class="jp">受かる</span> <span class="gloss">(うかる, to pass)</span> — to float up, to be accepted. You either fall or rise. Japanese frames academic fate as vertical motion.</p><p><span class="jp">落ちる</span> is intransitive — things fall by themselves. Its transitive partner is <span class="jp">落とす</span> <span class="gloss">(おとす, to drop)</span>. <span class="jp-example">りんごが落ちる</span> <span class="gloss">(an apple falls)</span> vs <span class="jp-example">りんごを落とす</span> <span class="gloss">(drop an apple)</span>. <span class="jp-example">成績が落ちる</span> <span class="gloss">(grades decline)</span> vs <span class="jp-example">成績を落とす</span> <span class="gloss">(let grades drop — you caused it)</span>.</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">落</span>: grass radical (<span class="jp">艹</span>) on top, water (<span class="jp">氵</span>) on the left. Rain dripping off leaves — water drops falling from foliage.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Particles:</span> <span class="jp">落ちる</span> takes <span class="jp highlight">が</span> for the thing that falls. <span class="jp-example">葉が落ちる</span> <span class="gloss">(leaves fall)</span>. For exams: <span class="jp-example">試験<span class="highlight">に</span>落ちる</span> — に marks what you fell at.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Passive:</span> Rare in literal sense. For "making fall," use the transitive <span class="jp">落とす</span>.</p><p class="particle-note"><span class="note-label">Causative:</span> <span class="jp">落とす</span> is used instead of the causative form in practice.</p><div class="verb-meta"><span class="group-badge">一段 Ichidan</span><span class="trans-badge">自動詞 — pair: 落とす (おとす)</span></div><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">おち</span><span class="ending">る</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">おち</span><span class="ending">ない</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Polite</td><td><span class="stem">おち</span><span class="ending">ます</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Polite neg</td><td><span class="stem">おち</span><span class="ending">ません</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">おち</span><span class="ending">た</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Polite past</td><td><span class="stem">おち</span><span class="ending">ました</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">おち</span><span class="ending">て</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Volitional</td><td><span class="stem">おち</span><span class="ending">よう</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Polite vol</td><td><span class="stem">おち</span><span class="ending">ましょう</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Passive</td><td><span class="stem">おち</span><span class="ending">られる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Causative</td><td><span class="stem">おち</span><span class="ending">させる</span></td><td class="particle">を／に</td></tr><tr><td>Caus-pass</td><td><span class="stem">おち</span><span class="ending">させられる</span></td><td class="particle">に</td></tr><tr><td>Potential</td><td><span class="stem">おち</span><span class="ending">られる</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Imperative</td><td><span class="stem">おち</span><span class="ending">ろ</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Imp なさい</td><td><span class="stem">おち</span><span class="ending">なさい</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～ば</td><td><span class="stem">おち</span><span class="ending">れば</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr><tr><td>Cond ～たら</td><td><span class="stem">おち</span><span class="ending">たら</span></td><td class="particle">が</td></tr></table>'

# 115: 息子 - lead with the breath etymology
lessons[115] = '<p><span class="jp">息</span> (breath) + <span class="jp">子</span> (child) = your breath-child. The child who carries your life force forward. <span class="jp">息</span> itself is <span class="jp">自</span> (nose/self) over <span class="jp">心</span> (heart) — breath flowing from nose to heart. Calling your son <span class="jp">息子</span> frames him as the continuation of your very breath.</p><p>Like <span class="jp">娘</span> (daughter), <span class="jp">息子</span> is humble speech — for <em>your own</em> son. For someone else\'s: <span class="jp-example">息子さん</span> with the polite suffix, or more formally <span class="jp-example">ご子息</span> <span class="gloss">(ごしそく)</span>.</p><p>An asymmetry worth noting: <span class="jp">娘</span> can refer to any young woman, but <span class="jp">息子</span> only means "son." It\'s locked to the parent-child relationship.</p>'

# 116: 白い - lead with cultural meaning
lessons[116] = '<p>White is the color of death in Japan. Not black — white. Funeral garments, mourning fabrics, the color of the beyond. But white is also purity, honesty, confession: <span class="jp-example">白状する</span> <span class="gloss">(はくじょうする, to confess — to make things white/clear)</span>. The color holds contradictions. It\'s the blank slate and the final page.</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">白</span> is believed to show the sun just above the horizon — the first pale light of dawn, before color fills the sky. White as absence, as the moment before the world paints itself.</p><p><span class="jp">白い</span> covers both the color and the concept of blankness: <span class="jp-example">白い紙</span> means both "white paper" and "blank paper." As a noun, drop the い: <span class="jp">白</span> <span class="gloss">(しろ)</span>. This noun/adjective pair exists for the four oldest colors in Japanese — <span class="jp">白/白い</span>, <span class="jp">黒/黒い</span>, <span class="jp">赤/赤い</span>, <span class="jp">青/青い</span> — the only colors with native い-adjective forms.</p><table class="conj-chart"><tr><td>Dictionary</td><td><span class="stem">しろ</span><span class="ending">い</span></td></tr><tr><td>Negative</td><td><span class="stem">しろ</span><span class="ending">くない</span></td></tr><tr><td>Past</td><td><span class="stem">しろ</span><span class="ending">かった</span></td></tr><tr><td>Past neg</td><td><span class="stem">しろ</span><span class="ending">くなかった</span></td></tr><tr><td>Adverb</td><td><span class="stem">しろ</span><span class="ending">く</span></td></tr><tr><td>て-form</td><td><span class="stem">しろ</span><span class="ending">くて</span></td></tr></table>'

# 117: 飛行機 - lead with compound transparency
lessons[117] = '<p><span class="jp">飛</span> (fly) + <span class="jp">行</span> (go) + <span class="jp">機</span> (machine). A flying-going-machine. Japanese compound nouns can be remarkably literal, and this is a textbook case — no metaphor, no ambiguity.</p><p>You know the first two kanji already. The third, <span class="jp">機</span>, means "machine" and shows up everywhere: <span class="jp-example">洗濯機</span> <span class="gloss">(せんたくき, washing machine)</span>, <span class="jp-example">機会</span> <span class="gloss">(きかい, opportunity — a mechanism of timing)</span>. When <span class="jp">機</span> sits at the end of a word, expect a device.</p><p><span class="jp-example">飛行機に乗る</span> <span class="gloss">(board a plane — literally "ride")</span> is the standard expression. Japan is an island nation; for international travel, there\'s no alternative to the <span class="jp">飛行機</span>.</p>'

# 118: 病気 - lead with the 気 connection
lessons[118] = '<p>In traditional East Asian medicine, illness is a disorder of <span class="jp">気</span> — your vital energy. When <span class="jp">気</span> is blocked or depleted, you\'re sick. <span class="jp">病気</span> isn\'t just "disease" — it\'s <em>sick energy</em>, your life force gone wrong. <span class="jp">病</span> (sick) + <span class="jp">気</span> (energy) tells a story that goes deeper than "illness."</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">病</span> has the sickness radical <span class="jp">疒</span> — a person lying on a bed. Every illness-related kanji uses it: <span class="jp">痛</span> (pain), <span class="jp">症</span> (symptom), <span class="jp">療</span> (treatment). Spot <span class="jp">疒</span> and you\'ve found medical vocabulary.</p><p><span class="jp-example">病気になる</span> <span class="gloss">(get sick — "become illness")</span>. <span class="jp-example">病気が治る</span> <span class="gloss">(recover)</span>. <span class="jp-example">病気で休む</span> <span class="gloss">(take time off due to illness)</span> — <span class="jp">で</span> marks the reason.</p>'

# 119: 冬 - lead with cultural texture
lessons[119] = '<p><span class="jp">冬</span> is the season of <span class="jp-example">鍋</span> <span class="gloss">(なべ, hot pot)</span>, <span class="jp-example">温泉</span> <span class="gloss">(おんせん, hot springs)</span>, <span class="jp-example">こたつ</span> <span class="gloss">(heated table you put your legs under)</span>, and New Year. Japan\'s four seasons structure the culture in ways that go far beyond weather. Seasonal vocabulary matters in conversation — people expect you to talk about the seasons and how they shape daily life.</p><p>The kanji <span class="jp">冬</span> in its oldest form showed two knotted threads — endings, the tying-off of the year\'s cycle. The two dots at the bottom (<span class="jp">冫</span>) are the ice radical, added later. Ice under a symbol of closure — winter.</p><p>The four seasons as a set: <span class="jp">春</span> <span class="gloss">(はる)</span>, <span class="jp">夏</span> <span class="gloss">(なつ)</span>, <span class="jp">秋</span> <span class="gloss">(あき)</span>, <span class="jp">冬</span> <span class="gloss">(ふゆ)</span>. All single-kanji, native readings, ancient vocabulary. <span class="jp-example">冬休み</span> <span class="gloss">(ふゆやすみ, winter vacation)</span> — the break around New Year.</p>'

# 120: 年 - lead with the harvest etymology
lessons[120] = '<p>The kanji <span class="jp">年</span> was a person carrying a bundle of grain. One harvest cycle = one year. Time measured not by calendars but by crops.</p><p><span class="jp">とし</span> means both "year" and "age," and the two blend seamlessly. <span class="jp-example">年を取る</span> <span class="gloss">(to age — "take years")</span>. <span class="jp-example">年が明ける</span> <span class="gloss">(the new year arrives — "the year opens")</span>. <span class="jp-example">いい年して</span> <span class="gloss">(at your age! — mild scolding)</span>. Time passing and growing older are the same word because they\'re the same thing.</p><p>Readings: <span class="jp">とし</span> for standalone use. <span class="jp">ねん</span> in compounds and as a counter: <span class="jp-example">三年</span> <span class="gloss">(さんねん)</span>, <span class="jp-example">去年</span> <span class="gloss">(きょねん)</span>, <span class="jp-example">来年</span> <span class="gloss">(らいねん)</span>. And the irregular one: <span class="jp-example">今年</span> <span class="gloss">(ことし — not こんねん)</span>. An old native reading that refused to be replaced.</p>'


